.Dd $Mdocdate$
.Dt ANYVAULT 1 URM
.Os ANYVAULT
.Sh NAME
.Nm anyvault
.Nd a password manager with a flexible storage backend
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
[options]
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a password manager that uses external commands to act as its storage
backend. Three separate commands need to be provided in the configuration file:
.Bl -bullet -width 2n
.It
an encrypt command that reads the JSON database on STDIN
.It
a decrypt command that outputs the JSON database on STDOUT
.It
a backup command that is called before the first encrypt in a session.
.El
The decrypted database is unloaded as soon as possible and its memory is
zeroed before being freed. See
.Sx SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
for the full threat model.

Launching the program leads to an an interactive prompt where commands can
be entered to manage and access secrets. The commands are:
.Bl -tag -width 6n -offset 2n
.It add
Add a new secret. The user will be prompted for various fields including
the secret itself. Values are limited in length as per the max_value_length
parameter from the configuration file.
.It change <entry>
Change one or multiple fields of the specified secret entry.
.It delete <entry>
Delete the specified secret entry.
.It help
Prints a list of available commands.
.It list
Lists all secret entries.
.It paste <entry>
Sends the specified entry's secret field to a paste command's STDIN. The
command invoked depends on the paste_cmd value of the configuration file.
See
.Sx SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
for the threat model.
.It quit
Quits the
.Nm session.
.It rename <entry>
Rename an entry to another name which will be asked interactively.
.It save
Save the database using the external command specified in the configuration
as encrypt_cmd.
.It show <entry>
Show the non-secret fields of the entry specified as an argument.
.It showall <entry>
Show all the fields of the entry specified as an argument, including the secret.
.It xtype <entry>
Use the X11 XTEST extension to emulate keypresses with the sequence of
characters stored in the secret. The command will not immediately start
sending keypresses; the user should first bring the cursor in the right place
then press the hotkey as specified in configuration file in the
xtype_hotkey parameter. The hotkey specified in the xtype_esc value can
be used to cancel sending keys. See
.Sx SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
for the threat model.
.El

The session will terminate automatically after a number of seconds has passed,
as specified in the timeout parameter in the configuration file.

Command-line options are:
.Bl -tag -width 6n -offset 2n
.It -h
Prints help
.It -v
Prints version
.It -d
Increase debug output
.It -c <configuration path>
Provide an alternate configuration path; the default is set according to the
XDG Base Directory Specification (typically under $HOME/.config/anyvault).
.It -x
Skip permission and ownership checks on the configuration file. By default,
.Nm
will refuse to start if the configuration is owned by another user or if
other users have read access to it.
.It -X
Don't disable core dump creation on crash. By default RLIMIT_CORE is set to
zero (disabling core dumps).
.El
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -offset 2n -width 6n
.It /usr/share/doc/anyvault/examples/anyvault.conf.sample
Example configuration file
.It /usr/share/doc/anyvault/examples/anyvault_backend_gpg.sh
Example storage backend using GnuPG
.El
.Sh SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
.Nm
assumes every process running as the invoking user is trusted. The X11
server has no isolation between clients connected to the same
.Ev DISPLAY ,
so any local process running as the user can attack secret retrieval.
There is no application-level defense against this; both retrieval
mechanisms are exposed.
.Pp
The
.Cm xtype
command maps each distinct character of the secret to a keycode in the
global X keyboard map, injects the keystrokes, then restores the
original map. It uses unused keycodes first, borrowing ordinary keys
only when the secret has more distinct characters than there are spare
keycodes. While it is typing, the secret's distinct characters are
present in the keyboard map, so a local X client polling
.Xr XGetKeyboardMapping 3
can read the character set. Exposure is transient and does not persist
on disk.
.Pp
The
.Cm paste
command writes the secret to an X selection (typically CLIPBOARD or
PRIMARY, via tools like
.Xr xclip 1
or
.Xr xsel 1 ) .
Any local X client can read it until the selection is replaced. Two
amplifiers are worth noting:
.Bl -bullet -width 2n
.It
Clipboard managers (clipit, parcellite, xfce4-clipman, Klipper, etc.)
commonly snapshot selections and write the history to disk, often
unencrypted under
.Pa ~/.cache
or
.Pa ~/.local/share .
This turns a transient leak into a persistent one. Configure your
clipboard manager to ignore
.Nm
output, or disable it, if you use
.Cm paste .
.It
Web browsers expose the clipboard to JavaScript. A focused malicious
page can read pasted content via paste-event listeners, and some
browsers expose
.Li navigator.clipboard.readText()
under user-gesture rules. There is no equivalent browser-side API for
reading the X keymap.
.El
.Pp
Limit clipboard exposure by using paste programs that release the
selection after one read, e.g.
.Ql xclip -selection clipboard -loops 1 .
.Pp
Neither mechanism is meaningfully safer than the other in general. If
your desktop runs a disk-persisting clipboard manager,
.Cm xtype
is likely the lesser exposure. If you regularly run untrusted code
that could be polling the keymap,
.Cm paste
with a one-shot clipboard tool may be preferable.
.Pp
The decrypted database is held only in memory while
.Nm
is running, in
.Xr mlock 2 Ns 'd
pages where possible, and is zeroed via
.Xr explicit_bzero 3
before being freed. Core dumps are disabled by default; see the
.Fl X
flag. Neither protection survives a process running as the user that
can
.Xr ptrace 2
.Nm .
.Sh BUGS
The
.Cm xtype
command uses the X11 XTEST extension via
.Xr XTestFakeKeyEvent 3
to inject synthetic keystrokes. Modern applications, notably web
browsers, may treat XTEST-injected events as untrusted and filter them
out for security-sensitive contexts such as password fields, autofill
targets, or sandboxed inputs. When this happens, the target receives no
input at all, regardless of focus state. There is no application-level
workaround; use the
.Cm paste
command in those cases instead.
.Pp
While
.Cm xtype
is running it temporarily modifies the global X keyboard map and
restores it when done, including when interrupted by an ordinary
terminating signal such as
.Dv SIGTERM
or
.Dv SIGINT .
It cannot recover from
.Dv SIGKILL
or a fatal fault such as
.Dv SIGSEGV ,
so a forced kill
.Pq Ql kill -9
or a crash while it is typing will leave its borrowed keycodes remapped,
and some keys will then produce the wrong characters. Recover by
reloading the keyboard map, for example with
.Xr setxkbmap 1 ,
or by logging out and back in.
